This is a known breaking change. **.NET 10 adopts edge-to-edge display by default** (required by Android 15), which makes `AdjustResize` no longer shrink your layout. You now need to respond to **window insets** instead.

### Quick fix — handle IME insets on Android

In your `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

    ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new KeyboardInsetsListener());
}

private class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
{
    public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
    {
        var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
        var navBarInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

        // Apply bottom padding = max of IME or nav bar height
        int bottomPadding = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navBarInsets.Bottom);
        v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottomPadding);

        return insets;
    }
}
```

### What this does

- When the keyboard opens, `Ime()` insets report its height → padding pushes your input bar up.
- When the keyboard closes, it falls back to the navigation bar inset.

### Also ensure in `AndroidManifest.xml`:

```xml
<activity android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" ... />
```

`adjustResize` is technically deprecated but still needed so the insets are dispatched correctly in edge-to-edge mode.

### Alternative: MAUI Community Toolkit

The `KeyboardAccelerator` behavior in the [Community Toolkit](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/communitytoolkit/maui/) can handle this declaratively if you prefer not to write platform code.
